"""
mkt-christ: Daniel 9–11 (93 verses)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-daniel-9-11.py

Ch9: Daniel's prayer of confession + the Seventy Weeks prophecy (the most concentrated
     Christological prophecy in the OT)
Ch10: The vision of the glorious man (direct source for Rev 1:13-16's portrait of Christ)
Ch11: The north-south king conflicts (types of the Antichrist), ending with the self-exalting
      king who is the template for 2 Thess 2:3-4

Interpretation decisions:
- The six infinitives of 9:24 are read as a summary of Christ's entire saving work
- 9:25-26: The anointed one = Jesus; "cut off" = crucifixion; 69-week calculation points to
  the Triumphal Entry or the crucifixion depending on the calculation method
- 10:5-6: The glorious man clothed in linen = an angel or a pre-incarnate Christ-figure;
  Revelation 1:13-16 treats the vision as a template for the glorified Christ
- 11:31: The "abomination of desolation" is read in light of Jesus's citation in Mark 13:14
- 11:36-39: The self-exalting king = type for 2 Thess 2:3-4's man of lawlessness
"""

import json, pathlib
ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DANIEL_CHRIST = {
    "9": {
        "1": "<p>Darius the Mede becomes king — the empire has shifted from Babylon to Medo-Persia. The political transition is the occasion for Daniel's greatest prayer. The son of David who would rule forever (2 Sam 7:13) has not yet come; the empires of the world rotate their dominion while YHWH's promised King waits in the prophetic horizon. The timing of Darius's reign frames Daniel's intercession: human kings rise and fall while the eternal King's coming is calculated in weeks.</p>",
        "2": "<p>Daniel understands from Jeremiah's prophecy (Jer 25:11; 29:10) that the 70-year desolation of Jerusalem is nearly complete. The attention to divinely appointed time — that even exile has a fixed duration — is the foundation for the Seventy Weeks prophecy that follows: just as exile had its appointed 70 years, the Messiah's advent has its appointed 490. Galatians 4:4 captures the same logic: 'When the fullness of time had come, God sent forth his Son' — Christ arrives at the end of the divinely measured period.</p>",
        "3": "<p>Daniel turns to the Lord in fasting, sackcloth, and ashes — the posture of extreme penitential intercession. This prayer becomes the occasion for the greatest Christological prophecy in the OT (vv. 24-27). The posture of self-abasement before God — the prophet identifying himself with the sins of his people — mirrors Christ's self-identification with human sin: 'He himself bore our sins in his body on the tree' (1 Pet 2:24). The intercessor who prays in sackcloth anticipates the Intercessor who wears a crown of thorns.</p>",
        "4": "<p>Daniel addresses YHWH as 'great and awesome God who keeps covenant and steadfast love' (<em>šōmēr habbĕrît wĕhahesed</em>) — the same covenant vocabulary used in the Mosaic renewal formulas. The prayer's opening identifies the covenantal framework within which the 70 years must be understood, and within which the Messiah's coming will operate. Christ is the one who keeps the covenant perfectly on Israel's behalf: 'this is my blood of the covenant which is poured out for many' (Matt 26:28) — the new covenant is YHWH's covenant-keeping fulfilled in his Son.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The confession accumulates verbs of sin: sinned, committed iniquity, done wickedly, rebelled, turned aside. Paul's similar accumulation in Romans 3:10-18 ('none righteous ... none who does good') draws from this same confessional vocabulary to establish universal human sinfulness as the premise for the gospel. The catalogue of human failure is the background against which Christ's obedience shines: 'by the one man's obedience the many will be made righteous' (Rom 5:19) — the answer to every verb of Daniel's confession.</p>",
        "6": "<p>Israel has not listened to YHWH's servants the prophets who spoke in his name to every class of society. The prophets were rejected — and Jesus identifies himself as the culmination of this rejected prophetic line: 'Jerusalem, Jerusalem, you who kill the prophets and stone those sent to you' (Matt 23:37). The rejection of the prophets that Daniel confesses is the pattern that ends in the rejection of the Son: 'He came to his own, and his own people did not receive him' (John 1:11).</p>",
        "7": "<p>To the Lord belongs righteousness; to Israel belongs shame in all the countries of their scattering. The contrast between divine righteousness and human shame is the theological baseline for justification. Christ takes the shame of the scattered exile-people upon himself (Heb 12:2: 'enduring the cross, despising the shame') and imputes to them the very righteousness that Daniel declares belongs to the Lord: 'the righteousness of God through faith in Jesus Christ for all who believe' (Rom 3:22).</p>",
        "8": "<p>Shame belongs to Israel's kings, princes, and fathers — the leadership class who bore responsibility for the covenant's maintenance. In Christ, the shame of the failed leadership is concentrated and absorbed: he is crucified between two criminals (Isa 53:12: 'numbered with the transgressors'), bearing the shame of all who betrayed the covenant. The reversal is complete at resurrection: 'God has highly exalted him and bestowed on him the name that is above every name' (Phil 2:9).</p>",
        "9": "<p>'To the Lord our God belong mercy and forgiveness, for we have rebelled against him.' The mercy (raḥamîm) and forgiveness (sĕliḥôt) that Daniel appeals to are not human achievements but divine attributes. Christ is the concrete form of this mercy and forgiveness: 'In him we have redemption through his blood, the forgiveness of our trespasses, according to the riches of his grace' (Eph 1:7). What Daniel appeals to as divine attributes, Paul announces as accomplished facts in the person of Christ.</p>",
        "10": "<p>Israel has not obeyed the voice of YHWH or walked in his Torah as set before them through the prophets. The failure to walk in the Torah — the pattern repeated through generations — defines the need for the new covenant of Jeremiah 31:31-34, in which the law is written on the heart. Christ fulfills both the law's demand (Matt 5:17) and the new covenant's promise (Heb 8:10), himself the one who walked perfectly in the Torah and now enables his people to do the same through the Spirit (Rom 8:4).</p>",
        "11": "<p>'The curse and oath written in the Law of Moses the servant of God have been poured out upon us, because we have sinned against him.' The curse of the law — systematically enumerated in Deuteronomy 28 — has fallen on the nation. Paul's Christology of the curse is the NT answer: 'Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us — for it is written, “Cursed is everyone who is hanged on a tree”' (Gal 3:13). The very curse Daniel confesses is the one Christ absorbs at the cross.</p>",
        "12": "<p>YHWH has confirmed his words against Jerusalem, bringing unprecedented disaster. The catastrophe of 586 BCE is the model for the judgment Jesus predicts for 70 CE (Matt 24:21: 'great tribulation, such as has not been from the beginning of the world until now'). But in both cases — 586 and 70 CE — judgment serves a redemptive purpose: the refining of a remnant who will receive the new covenant. Christ weeps over Jerusalem (Luke 19:41-44) as Daniel prays over it, both knowing the catastrophe that faithlessness brings.</p>",
        "13": "<p>'Yet we have not entreated the favor of the LORD our God, turning from our iniquities and paying attention to your truth.' The failure of repentance — Israel knows the judgment has come as written, yet does not seek the Lord's face. Jesus's call is precisely this turning: 'The time is fulfilled, and the kingdom of God is at hand; repent and believe in the gospel' (Mark 1:15). His advent is the moment when the face of YHWH to be sought becomes the face of the Son incarnate.</p>",
        "14": "<p>'The LORD has watched over the disaster and brought it upon us, for the LORD our God is righteous in all the works that he has done.' The theodicy of the exile: YHWH is righteous, not arbitrary. The same confession frames the cross: 'It was the will of the LORD to crush him; he has put him to grief' (Isa 53:10). The cross is the greatest concentration of divine justice in history — YHWH is righteous even there, perhaps especially there, where his righteousness is satisfied precisely through the crushing of his righteous Servant.</p>",
        "15": "<p>'O Lord our God, who brought your people out of the land of Egypt with a mighty hand ... we have sinned, we have done wickedly.' The Exodus is the paradigm of divine redemption — the 'mighty hand' (<em>yād ḥăzāqāh</em>) is the standard Exodus idiom. Jesus's Transfiguration conversation is about his 'exodus' which he was about to accomplish at Jerusalem (Luke 9:31). The greater Exodus — from sin and death rather than Egypt — is accomplished by the same God who stretched out his mighty hand, now incarnate in the Son who 'went out' to the cross.</p>",
        "16": "<p>'O Lord, according to all your righteous acts, let your anger and your wrath turn away from your city Jerusalem, your holy mountain.' Daniel prays for the wrath to turn away from Jerusalem and its holy mountain. The wrath turns away from the city permanently in Christ: Heb 12:22-24 announces that believers have come 'to Mount Zion ... to Jesus, the mediator of a new covenant, and to the sprinkled blood that speaks a better word than the blood of Abel.' The holy mountain's curse is lifted by the better blood.</p>",
        "17": "<p>'Now therefore, O our God, listen to the prayer of your servant and to his pleas for mercy, and for your own sake, O Lord, make your face shine upon your sanctuary that is desolate.' The petition — 'make your face shine upon your sanctuary' — echoes the Aaronic benediction (Num 6:25: 'the LORD make his face shine on you'). The face of God shines most fully in Christ: '2 Cor 4:6 — God who said, “Let light shine out of darkness,” has shone in our hearts to give the light of the knowledge of the glory of God in the face of Jesus Christ.'</p>",
        "18": "<p>'We do not present our pleas before you because of our righteousness, but because of your great mercy.' The basis of prayer is not merit but mercy — the foundation of all access to God in both Testaments. In Christ, mercy has a concrete form: 'Let us then with confidence draw near to the throne of grace, that we may receive mercy and find grace to help in time of need' (Heb 4:16). The throne of grace is the same mercy-seat Daniel appeals to, now made accessible through the great high priest.</p>",
        "19": "<p>'O Lord, hear; O Lord, forgive; O Lord, pay attention and act. Delay not, for your own sake, O my God, because your city and your people are called by your name.' The triple imperative of desperate prayer reaches its climax: 'Delay not!' This urgency — not for Daniel's sake but for the Lord's name — parallels the 'Thy kingdom come' of the Lord's Prayer and the 'Come, Lord Jesus' of Revelation 22:20. Christ himself in Gethsemane ('if it be possible, let this cup pass from me') and in Revelation 22:12 ('Behold, I am coming soon') inhabits both sides of this urgent prayer.</p>",
        "20": "<p>Daniel is speaking, praying, confessing sin, presenting his plea before YHWH his God 'for the holy mountain of my God.' The intercession is for the holy mountain — the place where God's name dwells. Jesus is the true holy mountain: Heb 12:22 ('you have come to Mount Zion') and John 4:23 ('the hour is coming when neither on this mountain nor in Jerusalem will you worship the Father') together announce that the holy mountain of Daniel's prayer is fulfilled in the person of Christ, who draws all worshipers to himself.</p>",
        "21": "<p>'While I was speaking in prayer, the man Gabriel, whom I had seen in the vision at the first, came to me in swift flight at the time of the evening sacrifice.' Gabriel — who later announces the birth of John the Baptist and the conception of Jesus (Luke 1:19-20, 26-38) — arrives at the time of the evening sacrifice. The evening offering is the tamid of Exod 29:41. Gabriel's appearances form a unified arc: to Daniel to announce the Messiah's timetable, then to Zechariah and Mary to announce his birth. The angel who carries the prophecy of the Messiah carries the birth announcement of the same Messiah.</p>",
        "22": "<p>'I have come to give you insight and understanding.' The angelic mission is epistemological: to give Daniel the ability to understand the divine plan. Jesus declares: 'The Father knows the Son and the Son knows the Father' (Matt 11:27), and 'No one knows the Father except the Son and anyone to whom the Son chooses to reveal him.' Christ is the one in whom 'are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge' (Col 2:3) — the insight that Gabriel brings to Daniel is a foretaste of the full revelation of God's wisdom in Christ.</p>",
        "23": "<p>'At the beginning of your pleas for mercy a word went out, and I have come to tell it to you, for you are greatly loved.' Daniel is addressed as <em>ḥămûdôt</em> (greatly loved, precious, desirable). The same word is used only a handful of times in the OT (cf. 10:11, 19). The 'greatly loved' address to Daniel prepares for the far greater 'beloved' addresses at Jesus's baptism ('This is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased,' Matt 3:17) and Transfiguration (Matt 17:5). The prophet called 'greatly loved' receives the prophecy of the one who is supremely beloved.</p>",
        "24": "<p>The six purposes of the Seventy Weeks are a compressed Christological program: (1) 'to finish the transgression' — Christ's atoning death stops the accumulation of covenant-breaking; (2) 'to put an end to sin' — justification abolishes sin's condemning power; (3) 'to atone for iniquity' — propitiation through his blood (Rom 3:25); (4) 'to bring in everlasting righteousness' — the imputed righteousness of Christ (2 Cor 5:21); (5) 'to seal both vision and prophet' — the fulfillment of all OT prophecy in Christ (2 Cor 1:20: 'all the promises of God find their Yes in him'); (6) 'to anoint a most holy place' — Christ's baptismal anointing (Luke 4:18: 'The Spirit of the Lord is upon me because he has anointed me') and the consecration of his body as the new temple. All six purposes are accomplished in Christ's first advent and its eschatological completion.</p>",
        "25": "<p>'Know therefore and understand that from the going out of the word to restore and build Jerusalem to the coming of an anointed one, a prince, there shall be seven weeks. Then for sixty-two weeks it shall be built again with squares and moat, but in a troubled time.' The Messiah is called '<em>māšîaḥ nāgîd</em>' (anointed prince/leader) — 'anointed' is the Hebrew source of both 'Messiah' and 'Christ.' The arithmetic points from Artaxerxes's decree (444 BCE, Neh 2:1-8) across 483 years (7+62 weeks × 7) toward the first century, consistently associated with Jesus's public ministry. The 69 weeks end at the coming of the Anointed One — the very title Jesus accepts at his baptism (Acts 10:38: 'God anointed Jesus of Nazareth with the Holy Spirit and with power').</p>",
        "26": "<p>'And after the sixty-two weeks, an anointed one shall be cut off and shall have nothing.' The crucifixion in prophetic foreground: <em>yikkārēt wĕʾên lô</em> — 'shall be cut off, with nothing belonging to him' or 'but not for himself.' 'Cut off' (<em>kārat</em>) is the vocabulary of judicial death in the Torah (Lev 7:20; Num 15:30-31). Isaiah 53:8 uses the same language: 'cut off out of the land of the living ... for the transgression of my people.' The Messiah who arrives in v. 25 is cut off in v. 26 — the Anointed One's death is the pivot of the entire 490-year program. The subsequent destruction of the city and sanctuary (70 CE) comes 'after' — the Messiah's death precedes even that judgment.</p>",
        "27": "<p>'And he shall make a strong covenant with many for one week, and for half of the week he shall put an end to sacrifice and offering.' The final week and the covenant confirmed with many: Jesus's three-and-a-half-year ministry culminates in the Last Supper ('this is my blood of the covenant, which is poured out for many,' Matt 26:28 — 'many' echoing v. 27's 'many'). In the middle of the week the sacrifice ends — at the cross, the veil of the temple is torn (Matt 27:51), the sacrificial system is made obsolete, and Christ's one sacrifice replaces all others (Heb 10:12: 'when Christ had offered for all time a single sacrifice for sins, he sat down at the right hand of God'). The 'abomination that makes desolate' in the second half of v. 27 is what Jesus cites in Mark 13:14 as the sign of coming judgment — connecting the 70th week's language to the end-time Antichrist figure.</p>"
    },
    "10": {
        "1": "<p>'A word was revealed to Daniel ... and the word was true, and it was about a great conflict.' The 'great conflict' (<em>ṣābāʾ gādôl</em>, great warfare/service) is the cosmic backdrop of the entire vision — the spiritual war behind earthly events. Paul names this same conflict in Eph 6:12: 'We do not wrestle against flesh and blood, but against the rulers, against the authorities, against the cosmic powers over this present darkness.' Christ is revealed in Daniel's vision as the one who presides over this conflict and whose victory determines its outcome.</p>",
        "2": "<p>Daniel mourns for three full weeks — the same period during which the heavenly messenger battles the prince of Persia (v. 13). The three weeks of sustained mourning become the context of revelation. Jesus taught his disciples to persist in prayer without losing heart (Luke 18:1-8: 'pray always and not lose heart'); the widow's persistent plea before the unjust judge is the picture of persistent intercession that Daniel models here.</p>",
        "3": "<p>Daniel eats no pleasant food, no meat or wine, and does not anoint himself for three weeks. The combination of dietary abstinence, non-anointing, and mourning constitutes a sustained Lenten posture. Christ fasts forty days in the wilderness (Matt 4:2) — a comparable season of spiritual preparation before the decisive conflict. In both cases, physical self-denial creates the receptive posture for divine revelation.</p>",
        "4": "<p>The vision comes by the Tigris on the twenty-fourth day of the first month. The first month is Nisan — the Passover month. On the fourteenth of Nisan the Passover lamb is sacrificed; ten days later Daniel receives this vision of the glorious man. The Passover-month context frames the vision: the imagery of the glorious deliverer received in the month of deliverance connects to Christ as the true Passover lamb (1 Cor 5:7: 'Christ, our Passover lamb, has been sacrificed').</p>",
        "5": "<p>'Behold, a man clothed in linen, with a belt of fine gold from Uphaz around his waist.' The man clothed in linen — the priestly garment (Lev 16:4; Ezek 9:2-3) — is the central figure of the vision. This description is the direct source for John's vision of the risen Christ in Revelation 1:13: 'one like a son of man, clothed with a long robe and with a golden sash around his chest.' The glory-figure of Daniel 10 becomes the glorified Christ of Revelation — whether this is an angel or a pre-incarnate Christophany, Revelation's identification of the same imagery with the ascended Jesus is deliberate.</p>",
        "6": "<p>'His body was like beryl, his face like the appearance of lightning, his eyes like flaming torches, his arms and legs like the gleam of burnished bronze, and the sound of his words like the sound of a multitude.' The four-part description — face like lightning, eyes like fire, limbs like burnished bronze, voice like many waters — is reproduced almost verbatim in Revelation 1:14-15 for the glorified Christ. The man of Daniel 10 is the visual vocabulary John uses to depict the risen Lord. However this figure is identified in Daniel's vision, Revelation declares: the man you saw, Daniel — that is Christ glorified.</p>",
        "7": "<p>The other men with Daniel do not see the vision, yet a great trembling falls on them and they flee to hide. Only Daniel remains, seeing the vision alone. This parallels the Transfiguration: only Peter, James, and John witness the glory of Christ (Matt 17:1-8); the other disciples wait below. The private revelation of divine glory — overwhelming those who are near even if they cannot see directly — is the experiential pattern of encounters with the holy.</p>",
        "8": "<p>'I was left alone and saw this great vision, and no strength was left in me. My radiant appearance was fearfully changed, and I retained no strength.' The encounter with divine glory strips away all human self-sufficiency. Paul's 'when I am weak, then I am strong' (2 Cor 12:10) is the NT articulation of this principle: only when Daniel's own strength is utterly depleted can he receive the strength the angel will give. Christ's kenōsis (Phil 2:7: 'emptied himself, taking the form of a servant') is the divine counterpart — the Son setting aside the exercise of divine prerogatives in order to enter fully into human weakness.</p>",
        "9": "<p>Daniel falls into a deep sleep when he hears the voice. The 'deep sleep' (<em>tardēmāh</em>) that falls on Daniel echoes Adam's deep sleep from which the bride was formed (Gen 2:21). Paul develops the same imagery: 'Husbands, love your wives, as Christ loved the church and gave himself up for her' (Eph 5:25-32) — the covenant-sleep of the bridegroom through whose self-giving the bride is created. The prophet's collapse before the divine voice is the pattern for the apostle's (Rev 1:17: 'When I saw him, I fell at his feet as though dead').</p>",
        "10": "<p>'And behold, a hand touched me and set me trembling on my hands and knees.' The restorative hand that raises Daniel from the ground — the gentle counter-action to the overwhelming divine presence. This motif of the touching hand appears three times in Daniel 10 (vv. 10, 16, 18) and once in 9:21. In Matthew 8:3, Jesus 'stretched out his hand and touched' the leper — the same restorative, equalizing touch from the holy to the unclean. The angel's hand in Daniel anticipates the hands of Christ, always reaching down to raise those who have fallen before the holy.</p>",
        "11": "<p>'O Daniel, man greatly loved, understand the words that I speak to you, and stand upright, for now I have been sent to you.' The address 'man greatly loved' (<em>ʾîš ḥămûdôt</em>) — the second time Daniel receives this designation (cf. 9:23). The command to 'stand upright' (<em>ʿemod</em>) before the messenger is the posture of readiness for service. Jesus's restorative commands follow the same pattern: to the paralytic, 'Get up and walk' (Matt 9:5); to the disciples prostrate at the Transfiguration, 'Rise, and have no fear' (Matt 17:7). The divine summons to stand upright is always a summons to renewed agency in God's service.</p>",
        "12": "<p>'From the first day that you set your heart to understand and humbled yourself before your God, your words have been heard, and I have come because of your words.' Prayer is heard from its beginning — not from the moment of answer but from the moment of petition. Hebrews 7:25 declares: 'He is able to save to the uttermost those who draw near to God through him, since he always lives to make intercession for them.' Christ intercedes continuously, not waiting for repeated petitions. The three weeks of apparent unanswered prayer (v. 2-3) concealed an answer already dispatched from the first day.</p>",
        "13": "<p>'The prince of the kingdom of Persia withstood me twenty-one days, but Michael, one of the chief princes, came to help me.' The angelic battle behind earthly history reveals a cosmic dimension to political events. Ephesians 6:12 explicitly names 'the rulers, the authorities, the cosmic powers over this present darkness' as the actual adversaries in the spiritual war. Christ's victory over these powers at the cross is the definitive resolution of this conflict: 'He disarmed the rulers and authorities and put them to open shame, by triumphing over them in him' (Col 2:15).</p>",
        "14": "<p>'I have come to make you understand what is to happen to your people in the latter days. For the vision is for days yet to come.' The angel's mission is to reveal the eschatological future of Daniel's people. Hebrews 1:2 declares that God 'in these last days has spoken to us by his Son' — the 'latter days' to which the vision points have now arrived in Christ. The Son is the final word after all the prophetic messengers; the vision Daniel receives points forward to the same events that Jesus addresses in the Olivet Discourse (Matt 24).</p>",
        "15": "<p>Daniel is struck dumb, his face toward the ground, unable to speak. The encounter with the divine presence has robbed him of speech — the same speechlessness that strikes Zechariah before Gabriel (Luke 1:20), and the same prostration that flattens John before the risen Christ (Rev 1:17). The inability to speak in the presence of holiness is not failure but appropriate response; the restoration of speech that follows is itself a divine gift. Christ restores speech to the mute (Matt 9:32-33) and to Zechariah (Luke 1:64) — the physical healings are enacted theology.</p>",
        "16": "<p>One in the form of a son of man touches Daniel's lips and restores his speech: 'O my lord, by reason of the vision pains have come upon me, and I retain no strength.' The touch on Daniel's lips mirrors Isaiah's burning coal (Isa 6:7: 'your guilt is taken away, your sin atoned for') and YHWH's touch on Jeremiah's mouth (Jer 1:9: 'I have put my words in your mouth'). In each case, the prophetic voice is given not possessed; speech about God is enabled by God. Christ — the Word who enables the prophetic word — is both the content of the speech and the one who makes it possible.</p>",
        "17": "<p>'How can my lord's servant talk with my lord? For now no strength remains in me, and no breath is left in me.' The rhetorical question — how can I speak before you? — is the radical incompetence of the human before the divine. Christ is both the one before whom this incompetence is real and the one who overcomes it: 'the Spirit helps us in our weakness. For we do not know what to pray for as we ought, but the Spirit himself intercedes for us with groanings too deep for words' (Rom 8:26). The breath that Daniel lacks, the Spirit supplies.</p>",
        "18": "<p>Again one having the appearance of a man touches Daniel and strengthens him. The triple strengthening (vv. 10, 16, 18) is the persistent, patient work of the divine messenger in the face of persistent weakness. Jesus strengthens his disciples after the Transfiguration (Matt 17:7) and in Gethsemane an angel comes to strengthen him (Luke 22:43). The pattern of divine strength administered through touch in moments of exhaustion runs from Daniel through the Gospels to the promise: 'My grace is sufficient for you, for my power is made perfect in weakness' (2 Cor 12:9).</p>",
        "19": "<p>'O man greatly loved, fear not, peace be with you; be strong and of good courage.' The threefold word — 'fear not, peace, be strong' — is the angelic benediction that prepares Daniel for the vision to follow. The risen Christ greets his disciples with the same sequence: 'Peace be with you' (John 20:19, 21, 26), 'Do not be afraid' (Matt 28:10), 'Take heart, I have overcome the world' (John 16:33). The angel's word to Daniel is the prototype of the risen Lord's word to his church — the same peace, the same courage, the same 'greatly loved' as the ground of the greeting.</p>",
        "20": "<p>'Do you know why I have come to you? But now I will return to fight against the prince of Persia; and when I go out, behold, the prince of Greece will come.' The heavenly being reveals the cosmic succession: the prince of Persia will yield to the prince of Greece. Earthly imperial succession has a spiritual dimension — each empire is animated by a governing spiritual power. Christ's victory at the cross is understood in Revelation as the definitive overthrow of 'the ruler of this world' (John 12:31): 'Now is the judgment of this world; now will the ruler of this world be cast out.' The series of imperial 'princes' Daniel describes ends in Christ's triumph.</p>",
        "21": "<p>'But I will tell you what is inscribed in the book of truth: there is none who contends by my side against these except Michael, your prince.' The 'book of truth' (<em>ketāb ʾĕmet</em>) — the heavenly register of what will certainly come to pass. Revelation 5 introduces the sealed scroll of God's purposes, which only the Lamb is worthy to open: what is inscribed in Daniel's book of truth is unsealed by Christ. Michael is Israel's protector (12:1); Christ is the church's high priest-king. The same heavenly book opens in Revelation — in Christ's hands — to reveal the outcome that Daniel could only glimpse.</p>"
    },
    "11": {
        "1": "<p>The angelic figure confirms that he also stood to support Darius the Mede in his first year. The heavenly involvement in the transition of empires is continuous — the succession from Babylon to Persia to Greece to Rome is not merely political but providentially ordered. Paul's declaration that 'there is no authority except from God, and those that exist have been instituted by God' (Rom 13:1) rests on this Danielic vision: the succession of empires is the outworking of divine sovereignty preparing the world for the fullness of time (Gal 4:4).</p>",
        "2": "<p>Three more Persian kings and then a fourth, the mightiest, who will stir up Greece. The prophetic foreshortening of Persian history prepares for the main event: the arrival of the mighty Greek king. The historical sweep emphasizes that no empire, however powerful, is permanent; all are temporary stewards of an authority that belongs ultimately to Christ: 'All authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me' (Matt 28:18) — the authority that passed through these empires is finally concentrated in the risen Lord.</p>",
        "3": "<p>'Then a mighty king shall arise, who shall rule with great dominion and do as he wills.' The mighty king of Greece — Alexander the Great — 'shall do as he wills' (<em>yaʿăśeh kiṣônô</em>): the absolute exercise of self-willed power. The contrast with Christ is pointed: Jesus does not do his own will but the Father's ('For I have come down from heaven, not to do my own will but the will of him who sent me,' John 6:38). The mighty king whose will is self-directed passes away (v. 4); the Son whose will is aligned with the Father receives an eternal kingdom (Dan 7:14).</p>",
        "4": "<p>'And as soon as he has arisen, his kingdom shall be broken and divided toward the four winds of heaven, but not to his posterity.' The brevity of Alexander's empire — the mightiest personal dominion in the ancient world shattered at his death. The contrast with Christ is sharp: Jesus establishes a kingdom 'that shall never be destroyed' (Dan 2:44) and his 'posterity' — those born again into his family — are innumerable (Ps 22:30; Isa 53:10: 'He shall see his offspring'). What Alexander could not pass on, Christ distributes as an inheritance to all who receive him (John 1:12).</p>",
        "5": "<p>The king of the south (Ptolemy I) grows strong; one of his princes becomes stronger still (Seleucus I). The jostling of the Diadochi — the competing heirs to Alexander's divided empire — begins the long north-south conflict that will devastate the 'beautiful land' (Israel). The covenant people are caught between empires, as the church will be caught between worldly powers in subsequent ages. Christ's promise 'I will never leave you nor forsake you' (Heb 13:5) is given to a community that will face precisely these competing pressures.</p>",
        "6": "<p>The failed alliance between north and south through political marriage — the daughter of the south given to the king of the north, but the alliance collapses. Political marriages as instruments of stability — the same system of human calculation that God's covenant transcends. Christ is not a political alliance but a covenant: 'the new covenant in my blood' (Luke 22:20) ratified by his own body, not by a diplomatic arrangement that can be broken when interests diverge.</p>",
        "7": "<p>A branch from her roots takes up his father's position and acts against the northern king's army. The ongoing warfare between Ptolemaic south and Seleucid north grinds on through generations. The cycle of revenge and counter-attack mirrors the 'wars and rumors of wars' that Jesus names as the background noise of the present age (Matt 24:6). He does not promise the end of such cycles before his return; he promises presence and ultimate victory through them.</p>",
        "8": "<p>The king of the south carries away Egyptian gods and precious vessels into Egypt and prevails for years. The stripping of the northern kingdom's divine images — a common ancient-world demonstration of the defeated gods' powerlessness — anticipates the NT proclamation that all idols are 'made with hands' and have no power over Christ's people. Col 2:15: 'He disarmed the rulers and authorities and put them to open shame, triumphing over them.' The Ptolemaic victory over Seleucid gods is a type for Christ's triumph over all spiritual powers.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The king of the north invades the southern kingdom and returns to his own land. The recurring incursion-and-withdrawal pattern of the north-south conflict. The back-and-forth of earthly warfare without resolution contrasts with the decisive 'once for all' character of Christ's victory: Heb 9:28 — 'Christ, having been offered once to bear the sins of many, will appear a second time, not to deal with sin but to save those who are eagerly waiting for him.' One decisive coming, not endless cycles of advance and withdrawal.</p>",
        "10": "<p>The sons of the north stir up war and one advances as far as the enemy's fortress. The escalating conflict between north and south (Antiochus III's campaigns against Egypt). The 'fortress' (<em>maʿôz</em>) that becomes a target in earthly warfare is the same word used in v. 39 for the false god of fortresses the Antichrist honors. Christ is 'my rock and my fortress' (Ps 18:2) — the true stronghold that no earthly campaign can overcome: 'The gates of hell shall not prevail against it' (Matt 16:18).</p>",
        "11": "<p>The king of the south marches out against the northern multitude, the multitude is given into his hand, and his heart is exalted. The temporary victory of the south at the battle of Raphia (217 BCE, Ptolemy IV vs. Antiochus III). Military pride at a single victory — the hubris that regularly precedes disaster in the book of Daniel (cf. Nebuchadnezzar in ch. 4). Christ's counter-word: 'Blessed are the meek, for they shall inherit the earth' (Matt 5:5) — the opposite disposition from the self-exalting victor.</p>",
        "12": "<p>The multitude is cast down; the victor's heart is exalted, yet he does not prevail, because Ptolemy IV wastes the advantage. The failure to consolidate victory through spiritual complacency is a recurring motif. The church that wins a battle and then 'does not prevail' through carelessness is warned throughout the NT: 'Let anyone who thinks that he stands take heed lest he fall' (1 Cor 10:12). Christ himself 'endures to the end' (Heb 12:2-3) — the model of consistent faithfulness without self-exaltation.</p>",
        "13": "<p>The king of the north returns with a multitude greater than the first, including many allies after some years. The patient rebuilding of power by Antiochus III, who eventually defeats Ptolemy V at Paneion (198 BCE). The geopolitical patience of Antiochus III — waiting years and building alliances — models the patient cunning that characterizes adversarial power in the NT too. The church's patience is of a different quality: waiting for Christ's return in active service rather than military buildup.</p>",
        "14": "<p>'Many shall rise against the king of the south, and the violent among your own people shall lift themselves up in order to fulfill the vision, but they shall fail.' The Jewish 'violent ones' (<em>ûbĕnê pārîṣê ʿammĕkā</em>) who collaborate with Antiochus III against Ptolemy, thinking they fulfill the prophetic vision — but they fall. The zealot impulse to force the fulfillment of prophetic vision through human violence is a recurring failure mode. Jesus resists this at every turn: he refuses to be made king by force (John 6:15), rebukes Peter's sword (Matt 26:52), and enters Jerusalem on a donkey rather than a war horse.</p>",
        "15": "<p>The king of the north captures the fortified city; the southern forces cannot stand. Antiochus III's conquest of the strongholds of the Levant. The fortress vocabulary (<em>ʿîr miṣṣārôt</em>, fortified city) and the theme of military inability to stand anticipate v. 39's 'god of fortresses' — the Antichrist who trusts in military might. Christ's summary: 'Everyone who hears these words of mine and does them will be like a wise man who built his house on the rock' (Matt 7:24) — the true fortress is his word, not military fortification.</p>",
        "16": "<p>'But he who comes against him shall do as he wills, and none shall stand before him. And he shall stand in the glorious land, with destruction in his hand.' The conqueror stands in the 'glorious land' (haṣṣĕbî) — the covenant land of Israel — with destruction. The beauty of the promised land becomes a military position. Christ's 'standing in the glorious land' is of a wholly different kind: he stands in Jerusalem not as a foreign conqueror but as the fulfillment of all the land's covenantal promises, declaring the year of the LORD's favor (Luke 4:18-21).</p>",
        "17": "<p>The northern king plans to enter with the strength of his whole kingdom, and to arrange terms, and shall give him the daughter of women to ruin it, but she shall not stand or be for him. The 'daughter of women' (Cleopatra I given to Ptolemy V) is intended as a political spy but instead supports her husband. Political marriages as instruments of empire — the manipulation of intimacy for power. The NT answer: the bride of Christ (Rev 19:7-8) is not a political arrangement but a covenant of genuine love, prepared by the Lamb for his own sake, not as an instrument of domination.</p>",
        "18": "<p>He turns to the coastlands and captures many, but a commander halts his reproach; the reproach is turned back on him. The Roman legatus Popilius Laenas turns Antiochus III back at Eleusis (168 BCE). The halting of an empire's advance by an unexpected confrontation. The 'reproach' (<em>ḥerpāh</em>) that is turned back on its perpetrator anticipates the great reversal in Christ: Christ who bore reproach (Ps 22:6; Heb 13:13) has all reproach returned on the adversary who cast it — 'he who is in you is greater than he who is in the world' (1 John 4:4).</p>",
        "19": "<p>He returns to the fortresses of his own land, stumbles, falls, and is no more. Antiochus III dies in a failed campaign in Elam (187 BCE) — the mighty king who touched the glorious land comes to an ignoble end. The pattern of worldly power: rise, domination, stumble, end. Christ's trajectory is precisely inverted: descent, suffering, death — and then exaltation to the right hand of the Father. 'He humbled himself by becoming obedient to the point of death ... therefore God has highly exalted him' (Phil 2:8-9).</p>",
        "20": "<p>His successor sends an exactor of tribute through the glorious kingdom, but he shall be broken in neither anger nor battle within a few days. Seleucus IV, who sends Heliodorus to plunder the Jerusalem temple treasury (2 Macc 3) and is then assassinated. The brief, undistinguished reign of one who treats the holy place as a revenue source. The contrast with Christ's relation to the sanctuary is complete: Jesus cleanses the temple of its commercialization (John 2:14-17) rather than exploiting it for revenue, embodying what the temple was always meant to be.</p>",
        "21": "<p>'In his place shall arise a contemptible person to whom royal honor has not been given. He shall come in without warning and obtain the kingdom by flatteries.' Antiochus IV Epiphanes — the 'contemptible person' (<em>nibzeh</em>) who seizes power through intrigue rather than legitimate succession. He is the primary Antichrist type in the OT. The contrast with Christ is exact: Jesus receives his kingdom not by flattery but by the Father's eternal decree ('You are my Son; today I have begotten you,' Ps 2:7) and by the completed work of redemption ('worthy is the Lamb who was slain, to receive power,' Rev 5:12).</p>",
        "22": "<p>'Armies shall be utterly swept away before him and broken, even the prince of the covenant.' The 'prince of the covenant' (<em>nĕśî bĕrît</em>) swept away is the high priest Onias III, murdered in 171 BCE — the legitimate covenantal office holder destroyed by the contemptible person. The murder of the legitimate high priest by the Antichrist-type foreshadows the execution of Jesus, the true high priest. But Christ cannot be permanently 'swept away': Heb 7:24 — 'he holds his priesthood permanently, because he continues forever.'</p>",
        "23": "<p>'And from the time that an alliance is made with him he shall act deceitfully, and he shall become strong with a small people.' Antiochus IV's duplicitous rise — working through deception with a small base. The vocabulary of deception (<em>mirmāh</em>, deceit) is the characteristic mark of the adversarial power in apocalyptic literature. Satan is 'the father of lies' (John 8:44); the Antichrist in 2 Thess 2:9 comes 'with all wicked deception.' Christ's contrast: 'No deceit was found in his mouth' (1 Pet 2:22, quoting Isa 53:9) — the truth-teller against the deceiver.</p>",
        "24": "<p>He enters the richest districts of the province and does what his fathers never did — scattering plunder, spoil, and goods among his followers to buy loyalty. The corruption of patronage — distributing stolen wealth to secure political allegiance. The NT critique of this worldly pattern: 'You know that the rulers of the Gentiles lord it over them, and their great ones exercise authority over them. It shall not be so among you' (Matt 20:25-26). Christ distributes not plunder but himself — his body and blood given for many.</p>",
        "25": "<p>He stirs up his power against the king of the south with a great army. The first campaign of Antiochus IV against Egypt (169 BCE). Military buildup and the cultivation of power — the posture of worldly kingdoms. The NT diagnosis: 'What causes quarrels and what causes fights among you? Is it not this, that your passions are at war within you?' (Jas 4:1). The wars between north and south begin in the hearts of those who love domination; Christ's kingdom begins in the heart's surrender.</p>",
        "26": "<p>Those who eat his food shall break him; his army is swept away and many fall down slain. Treachery from Antiochus IV's own advisors. The betrayal-from-within pattern — the one fed at the king's table who destroys him — has a terrible inversion in the Passion narrative: Judas, who ate at Jesus's table (John 13:18: 'he who ate my bread has lifted his heel against me,' citing Ps 41:9), betrays him. But in Christ's case the betrayal becomes the instrument of redemption, not destruction.</p>",
        "27": "<p>'And as for the two kings, their hearts shall be bent on doing evil. They shall speak lies at the same table, but to no avail, for the end is yet to be at the time appointed.' Both kings deceive each other at the conference table — the diplomatic summit as theater of mutual deception. The 'appointed time' (<em>lammôʿēd</em>) governs even the deceptions of kings: God's timetable overrides human scheming. Christ declares: 'the hour is coming, and is now here' (John 5:25) — the appointed time is not merely governing the kings of the north and south but the hour of the Son of Man's glorification (John 12:23).</p>",
        "28": "<p>'And he shall return to his land with great wealth, but his heart shall be set against the holy covenant. And he shall work his will and return to his own land.' The 'holy covenant' (<em>bĕrît qōdeš</em>) against which Antiochus IV sets his heart — the Mosaic covenant and its cultic practices. Christ is the fulfillment and guarantor of the holy covenant: 'This cup that is poured out for you is the new covenant in my blood' (Luke 22:20). What Antiochus opposes, Christ seals; what Antiochus defiles, Christ cleanses; what Antiochus destroys, Christ restores and surpasses.</p>",
        "29": "<p>At the appointed time he returns south, but this time it shall not be as before. The second campaign against Egypt is cut short by Rome's intervention (168 BCE, the 'Day of Eleusis'). The 'appointed time' (<em>lammôʿēd</em>) is YHWH's calendar, not Antiochus's. The same principle governs Christ's ministry: 'My hour has not yet come' (John 2:4; 7:30; 8:20) until 'Father, the hour has come' (John 17:1). The divine appointment of times is the backbone of redemptive history.</p>",
        "30": "<p>Ships of Kittim come against him, and he is discouraged and returns; he is furious against the holy covenant and takes action. Antiochus IV, humiliated by Rome, turns his fury against the Jews. The pattern: imperial humiliation redirected as violence against the covenant people. The church is warned of the same misdirected fury: 'the devil has come down to you in great wrath, because he knows that his time is short' (Rev 12:12). The short time of the adversary's rage is bounded by the same divine appointment that bounded Antiochus's campaigns.</p>",
        "31": "<p>'Forces from him shall appear and profane the temple and fortress, and shall take away the regular burnt offering. And they shall set up the abomination that makes desolate.' The desecration of the temple in 167 BCE — the abolition of the tamid and the erection of an idol on the altar. Jesus cites this very verse in Mark 13:14: 'when you see the abomination of desolation spoken of by the prophet Daniel, standing where he ought not to be ... then let those who are in Judea flee to the mountains.' The Antiochean desecration becomes the type for the end-time desecration that precedes Christ's return. The abomination that makes desolate is answered by the one who makes holy: Christ, the true temple, whose body was destroyed and raised (John 2:19).</p>",
        "32": "<p>'He shall seduce with flattery those who violate the covenant, but the people who know their God shall stand firm and take action.' The key distinction: those who 'know their God' (<em>yōdĕʿê ʾĕlōhāyw</em>) stand firm against the seduction of flattery. Jesus distinguishes his sheep from the rest by knowledge: 'I know my own and my own know me' (John 10:14). The mutual knowledge between shepherd and sheep is the same 'knowing God' that enables the Maccabean faithful to resist. The NT term for the persevering saints — those who 'endure to the end' (Matt 24:13) — is the equivalent community.</p>",
        "33": "<p>'And the wise among the people shall make many understand, though for some days they shall stumble by sword and flame, by captivity and plunder.' The teachers who instruct the many (<em>maśkîlê ʿam</em>) — the Hasidim or early Pharisees — suffer martyrdom. The paradigm of teaching-through-suffering: Jesus himself is 'the way, the truth, and the life' (John 14:6) whose own suffering is the supreme teaching. Hebrews 11 catalogues the cloud of witnesses who instructed through their endurance; Christ is the 'founder and perfecter of our faith' whose cross is the definitive teaching (Heb 12:2).</p>",
        "34": "<p>'When they stumble, they shall receive a little help. And many shall join themselves to them with flattery.' The little help in time of persecution — possibly the Maccabees — is partial, and is contaminated by insincere adherents. The church age is similarly characterized by incomplete help and mixed membership. Jesus's parable of the wheat and tares (Matt 13:24-30) addresses exactly this: insincere joiners mingle with genuine disciples until the harvest. The 'little help' points forward to the complete help that comes only at the appearing of the Son of Man.</p>",
        "35": "<p>'And some of the wise shall stumble, so that they may be refined, purified, and made white, until the time of the end, for it still awaits the appointed time.' The suffering of the wise has a purifying purpose — '<em>liṣrôp ûlĕbarrēr ûlĕlabbēn</em>' (to refine, to purify, to make white). Revelation 7:14 uses this very language: 'They have washed their robes and made them white in the blood of the Lamb.' The refinement Daniel foresees for the Maccabean period is the same refinement the church undergoes — with the crucial difference that the whitening agent is not suffering alone but the blood of Christ applied through suffering.</p>",
        "36": "<p>'And the king shall do as he wills. He shall exalt himself and magnify himself above every god, and shall speak astonishing things against the God of gods. He shall prosper till the indignation is accomplished; for what is decreed shall be done.' The self-exalting king who magnifies himself above every god — the template for the ultimate adversary. Paul draws directly from this verse in 2 Thess 2:4: the man of lawlessness 'opposes and exalts himself against every so-called god or object of worship, so that he takes his seat in the temple of God, proclaiming himself to be God.' Christ is the anti-type: Phil 2:6 — though he 'was in the form of God, he did not count equality with God a thing to be grasped' — the one who truly is God and refuses to grasp it, against the one who is not God and grasps it.</p>",
        "37": "<p>'He shall pay no attention to the gods of his fathers, or to the one beloved by women, nor pay attention to any other god, for he shall magnify himself above all.' The negation of all prior religious loyalty — the self-exalting king worships only himself. The NT Antichrist is similarly characterized by absolute self-reference: 'he takes his seat in the temple of God, proclaiming himself to be God' (2 Thess 2:4). The absence of the 'one beloved by women' (possibly the fertility deity Tammuz, or the Messiah of Jewish hope) is consistent with an end-time figure who rejects the Messianic claim.</p>",
        "38": "<p>'He shall honor the god of fortresses instead of these. A god whom his fathers did not know he shall honor with gold and silver, with precious stones and costly gifts.' The 'god of fortresses' (<em>ʾĕlôah maʿûzzîm</em>) — military power deified. The ultimate Antichrist worships strength itself. The contrast with Christ is complete: 'My kingdom is not of this world. If my kingdom were of this world, my servants would have been fighting' (John 18:36). Christ refuses the military fortresses of worldly kingship; the Antichrist makes them his god.</p>",
        "39": "<p>He deals with the strongest fortresses, honors those who acknowledge him, and divides the land for a price. The distribution of conquered territory as political patronage — the land itself treated as a commodity. The land of Israel as currency for the self-exalting king contrasts with the NT eschatology of inheritance: 'Blessed are the meek, for they shall inherit the earth' (Matt 5:5). The land that the Antichrist sells, Christ gives as inheritance to the meek who receive it from him as gift, not conquest.</p>",
        "40": "<p>'At the time of the end, the king of the south shall attack him, and the king of the north shall rush against him like a whirlwind, with chariots and horsemen and with many ships.' The final military campaign of the 'time of the end' (<em>ʿēt qēṣ</em>). The warfare of the end-time — chariots, horsemen, ships — is the escalating violence that precedes the Parousia. Revelation 6:1-8 catalogues the same spectrum of end-time violence (conquest, war, famine, death) that precedes Christ's appearing. The gathering of the nations for war is the penultimate moment before the ultimate resolution.</p>",
        "41": "<p>He enters the glorious land and many countries shall be overthrown, but Edom, Moab, and the main part of the Ammonites shall escape his hand. The selective destruction at the end of history — some nations escape; others do not. The motif of the 'glorious land' invaded and violated reaches its final iteration here: the land that belongs to YHWH's covenant people is the focal point of the last great assault. Christ's Parousia is the answer to this final assault — Zech 14:2-4: 'all the nations will be gathered against Jerusalem ... and the LORD will go out and fight against those nations.'</p>",
        "42": "<p>He stretches his hand against the countries, and Egypt shall not escape. The extension of the adversarial power's reach across the nations — no human power can provide sanctuary. The NT parallel: in the tribulation period, those without the mark cannot buy or sell (Rev 13:17). The apparent omnipotence of the end-time adversary — 'who is like the beast, and who can fight against it?' (Rev 13:4) — is the darkness before the dawn. Christ's return is the reversal of this apparent omnipotence.</p>",
        "43": "<p>He shall rule over the treasures of gold and silver and all the precious things of Egypt, and Libya and Cush shall follow in his train. The end-time king controls the wealth of the nations. Revelation 18 describes the same concentration of global wealth in Babylon the Great, whose fall is mourned by the merchants of the earth. The redistribution of wealth that Christ accomplishes is the antithesis of Babylon's hoarding: the new Jerusalem has gates always open, and the nations bring their glory into it (Rev 21:25-26) — free access rather than controlled accumulation.</p>",
        "44": "<p>News from east and north shall alarm him, and he shall go out with great fury to destroy and devote many to destruction. The adversarial king's final campaign — driven by alarm rather than strategy, by fury rather than purpose. The contrast with Christ's Second Coming could not be greater: Christ returns not in alarm but in certainty, not in fury but in righteous judgment, not to destroy recklessly but to 'destroy the destroyer of the earth' (Rev 11:18) and to save those who are eagerly waiting for him (Heb 9:28).</p>",
        "45": "<p>'And he shall pitch his palatial tents between the sea and the glorious holy mountain. Yet he shall come to his end, with none to help him.' The adversary's final camp pitched between the Mediterranean and the 'glorious holy mountain' — between sea and Jerusalem. He comes to his end — <em>wĕʾên ʿōzēr lô</em> (with none to help him) — the final isolation of the adversarial power. Rev 19:20: the beast 'was captured ... and thrown alive into the lake of fire.' The 'none to help' echoes Christ's own desolation at the cross (Ps 22:11) but with opposite meaning: Christ's 'none to help' is redemptive; the adversary's is final judgment. On the holy mountain where the adversary camps, Christ will return to reign (Zech 14:4; Acts 1:11-12).</p>"
    }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'daniel')
    merge_comm(existing, DANIEL_CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'daniel', existing)
    for ch in ['9', '10', '11']:
        vv = existing.get(ch, {})
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(vv)} verse(s) with christ commentary')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
